@newsubsection{5.1.2,OBJECT-COMPUTER}
@diagram{OBJECT-COMPUTER,ED-OBJECT-COMPUTER,ED-OBJECT-COMPUTER,ED-OBJECT-COMPUTER}@p This paragraph describes the computer upon which the program will execute.
@enumerate
@p @item The @term{computer-name}, if specified, must immediately follow the @syntax{OBJECT-COMPUTER} paragraph name.  The remaining clauses may be coded in any sequence.
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{CHARACTER}, @syntax{IS}, @syntax{PROGRAM} and @syntax{SEQUENCE} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The value specified for @term{computer-name}, if any, is irrelevant provided it is a valid COBOL word that does not match any GnuCOBOL reserved word.  The @term{computer-name} may include spaces.  This need not match the @term{computer-name} used with the @syntax{SOURCE-COMPUTER} paragraph, if any.
@p @item The @syntax{OBJECT-COMPUTER} paragraph is not allowed in a nested subprogram --- nested programs will inherit the @syntax{OBJECT-COMPUTER} settings of their parent program.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{COLLATING SEQUENCE} clause allows you to specify a customized character collating sequence to be used when alphanumeric values are compared to one another.  Data will still be stored in the character set native to the computer, but the logical sequence in which characters are ordered for comparison purposes can be altered from that defined by the computer's native character set.  The @term{alphabet-name-1} you specify needs to be defined in the @syntaxref{SPECIAL-NAMES} paragraph.
@p @item If no @syntax{COLLATING SEQUENCE} clause is specified, the collating sequence implied by the character set native to the computer (usually ASCII) will be used.
@p @item The optional @syntaxidx{CLASSIFICATION} clause may be used to specify a locale for the environment in which the program will be executing, for the purpose of influencing the upper-case and lower-case mappings of characters for the @syntaxref{UPPER-CASE} and @syntaxref{LOWER-CASE} intrinsic functions and the classification of characters for the @syntax{ALPHABETIC}, @syntax{ALPHABETIC-LOWER} and @syntax{ALPHABETIC-UPPER} class tests.  The definitions of these classes will be taken from the cultural convention specification (@syntax{LC_CTYPE}) from the specified locale.
@p The meanings of the four locale specifications are as follows:
@enumerate A
@p @item @term{locale-name-1} references a @syntaxrefalt{LOCALE,SPECIAL-NAMES} definition.
@p @item The keyword @syntax{LOCALE} refers to the current locale (in effect at the time the program is executed)
@p @item The keyword @syntax{USER-DEFAULT} references the default locale specified for the user currently executing this program.
@p @item The keyword @syntax{SYSTEM-DEFAULT} denotes the default locale specified for the computer upon which the program is executing.
@end enumerate
@item Absence of a @syntax{CLASSIFICATION} clause will cause character classification to occur according to the rules for the computer's native character set (ASCII, EBCDIC, @dots{}).
@end enumerate
