@p The @syntax{SPECIAL-NAMES} paragraph provides a means for specifying various program and operating environment configuration options.
@enumerate
@p @item The various clauses that may be specified within the @syntax{SPECIAL-NAMES} paragraph may be coded in any order.
@p @item The reserved word @syntax{IS} is optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of this word has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The @syntax{SPECIAL-NAMES} paragraph is not allowed in a nested subprogram --- nested programs will inherit the @syntax{SPECIAL-NAMES} settings of their parent program.
@p @item Only the final clause specified within this paragraph should be terminated with a period.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{CALL-CONVENTION} clause allows a decimal integer, representing a series of ON/OFF switch settings, to be associated with a mnemonic name which may then be coded on a @statementref{CALL}.  The switch settings defined by this mnemonic will then control how the linkage to a subroutine invoked by the @syntax{CALL} statement that references @term{mnemonic-name-1} will be handled.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{CONSOLE IS CRT} clause, if specified, will cause a @statement{DISPLAY} lacking an explicit @syntax{UPON} clause to be treated as a @statementref{DISPLAY screen-data-item}, and any @statement{ACCEPT} lacking a @syntax{FROM} clause to be treated as a @statementref{ACCEPT screen-data-item}.
@p @item If the @syntaxidx{CRT STATUS} clause is not specified, an implicit @syntaxidx{COB-CRT-STATUS} identifier (with a @syntax{PICTURE 9(4)}) will be allocated for the purpose of receiving screen @syntax{ACCEPT} statuses.  If @syntax{CRT STATUS} is specified, then @term{identifier-1} must be defined in the program as a @syntax{PICTURE 9(4)} field.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{CURRENCY SIGN} clause may be used to redefine the character to be used as a currency sign in a @syntaxref{PICTURE} clause.  The default currency sign is a dollar-sign ($).  You may specify any character @i{except} @syntax{0}-@syntax{9}, @syntax{A}-@syntax{Z}, @syntax{a}-@syntax{z}, @syntax{+}, @syntax{-}, @syntax{,}, @syntax{.}, @syntax{*}, @syntax{/}, @syntax{;}, @syntax{(}, @syntax{)}, @syntax{=}, @syntax{\\}, quote (") or space.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{CURSOR IS} clause allows you to specify a 4- or 6-character data item into which the cursor screen location at the time a screen @syntax{ACCEPT} is satisfied.  The value will be returned as @i{rrcc} or @i{rrrccc}, depending upon the length of the specified @term{identifier-2}, where @i{rr} and @i{rrr} represent the row number (starting at zero) and @i{cc} and @i{ccc} represent the column number (also starting at zero).  There is no default data item allocated for this data if the @syntax{CURSOR IS} clause is not specified, and it is the programmer's responsibility to define @term{identifier-2} if the clause is specified.
