@comment ** 5.1.3.1 Alphabet-Name-Clause                                    **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newunit{5.1.3.1,Alphabet-Name-Clause}
@diagram{SPECIAL-NAMES Alphabet-Clause,ED-SPECIAL-NAMES-AN-Info,ED-SPECIAL-NAMES-AN-TeX,None}
@diagram{SPECIAL-NAMES ALPHABET Literal-Clause,ED-SPECIAL-NAMES-L-Info,ED-SPECIAL-NAMES-L-TeX,None}@p The @syntaxidx{ALPHABET} clause provides a means for relating a name to a specified character code set or collating sequence, including those you define yourself using the @term{literal-1} option.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved word @syntax{IS} is optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of this word has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{THRU} and @syntax{THROUGH} are interchangeable.
@p @item GnuCOBOL considers @syntaxidx{ASCII}, @syntaxidx{STANDARD-1} and @syntaxidx{STANDARD-2} to be interchangeable.
@p @item @syntaxidx{NATIVE} specifies the system default character set.
@p @item The following points apply to using the @term{literal-n} specifications to compose a custom character set:
@enumerate A
@p @item The @term{literal-n} values are either integers or alphanumeric quoted characters.  These represent a single character in the @syntax{NATIVE} character set, either by it's actual text value (alphanumeric quoted character) or by ordinal position in the @syntax{NATIVE} character set (integer),
@p @item The sequence in which characters are defined in this clause specifies the relative order those characters should have when comparisons are made using this alphabet.
@p @item Character positions in this list do not affect the actual binary storage values used for the characters --- binary values will still be those of the @syntax{NATIVE} character set.
@p @item You may specify any of the figurative constants @syntax{SPACE}, @syntax{SPACES}, @syntax{ZERO}, @syntax{ZEROS}, @syntax{ZEROES}, @syntax{QUOTE}, @syntax{QUOTES}, @syntax{HIGH-VALUE}, @syntax{HIGH-VALUES}, @syntax{LOW-VALUE} or @syntax{LOW-VALUES} for any of the @term{literal-1}, @term{literal-2} or @term{literal-3} specifications.
@end enumerate
@item Once you have defined an alphabet name, that alphabet name may be used on specifications in @syntax{CODE-SET}, @syntax{COLLATING SEQUENCE}, or @syntax{SYMBOLIC CHARACTERS} clauses elsewhere in the program.
@end enumerate
