@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newunit{5.1.3.2,Class-Definition-Clause}
@diagram{SPECIAL-NAMES Class-Definition-Clause,ED-SPECIAL-NAMES-CD,ED-SPECIAL-NAMES-CD,None}
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved word @syntax{IS} is optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of this word has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{THRU} and @syntax{THROUGH} are interchangeable.
@p @item  Both @term{literal-1} and @term{literal-2} must be alphanumeric literals of length 1.
@p @item  The literal(s) specified on this clause define the possible characters that may be found in a data item's value in order to be considered part of the class.
@p @item For example, the following defines a class called "Hexadecimal", the definition of which specifies the only characters that may be present in an alphanumeric data item if that data item is to be part of the "Hexadecimal" class:
@example

CLASS Hexadecimal IS '0' THRU '9'
                     'A' THRU 'F'
                     'a' THRU 'f'
@end example
@item Once class "Hexadecimal" has been defined, program code could then use a statement such as @syntax{IF input-item IS Hexadecimal} to determine if the value of characters in a data item are valid according to that class.
@end enumerate
