@newunit{5.1.3.3,Switch-Definition-Clause}
@diagram{SPECIAL-NAMES Switch-Definition-Clause,ED-SPECIAL-NAMES-SD,ED-SPECIAL-NAMES-SD,None}@p The switch-definition clause associates a condition-name with a run-time execution switch so that the status of that switch may be tested from within a program.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{IS} and @syntax{STATUS} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The valid @term{switch-name-1} names are @syntaxidx{SWITCH-n} (n=0-36).
@p @item If the program is compiled with the @switchidx{-fsyntax-extension}, the switch names @syntaxidx{SWn} (n=0-15) are also valid; they correspond to @syntax{SWITCH-0} through @syntax{SWITCH-15}, respectively as well as @syntax{SWITCH-16} through @syntax{SWITCH-36}, @syntax{SWITCH 0} through @syntax{SWITCH 26} and @syntax{SWITCH A} through @syntax{SWITCH Z}.
@p @item At execution time, each switch will be associated with a @envvarruntimeref{COB_SWITCH_n}, where "n" will have the value "0" through "15".  Any of these sixteen environment variables that have the value "ON" (regardless of upper- or lower-case value) will be considered to be set "on".  Any of these sixteen environment variables having no value at all or a value other than "ON" will be considered "OFF".
@p @item Each specified switch must have at least one of a @syntax{IS @term{mnemonic-name-1}}, @syntax{ON STATUS} or an @syntax{OFF STATUS} option defined for it, otherwise there will be no way to reference the switch from within a GnuCOBOL program.
@p @item The @syntax{IS @term{mnemonic-name-1}} syntax provides a means for setting the switch to either an ON or OFF value via the @statementref{SET}.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{ON STATUS} and @syntaxidx{OFF STATUS} syntax provides a way of associating a condition-name with either the on or off status of the switch, so that status may be tested at execution time via the @statementref{IF}.
@end enumerate
