@newsubsection{5.2.1,SELECT}
@diagram{SELECT Statement,ED-SELECT,ED-SELECT,ED-SELECT}
@p The @statement{SELECT} creates a definition of a file and links that COBOL definition to the external operating system environment.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{AREAS}, @syntax{IS}, @syntax{MODE}, @syntax{OTHER}, @syntax{SEQUENCE}, @syntax{TO}, @syntax{USING} and @syntax{WITH} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item After @term{file-name-1}, the various clauses may be coded in any sequence.
@p @item A period must follow the last coded clause.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{OPTIONAL} clause, to be used only for files that will be used to provide input data to the program, indicates the file may or may not actually be available at run-time.  Attempts to @syntax{OPEN} an @syntax{OPTIONAL} file when the file does not exist will receive a special non-fatal file status value (see status 05 in the list of file status values below) indicating the file is not available; a subsequent attempt to @syntax{READ} that file will return an @syntax{AT END} (end-of-file) condition.  Optionally, files may be designated as @syntax{NOT OPTIONAL}, if desired.  This is useful when specifying the compiler's @switchidx{-foptional-file}, which automatically makes all files @syntax{OPTIONAL} except for those explicitly declared as @syntax{NOT OPTIONAL}.
@p @item The @term{file-name-1} value that you specify will be the name by which you will reference the file within your program.  This name should be formed according to the rules for user-defined names (@pxref{User-Defined Words}).
@p @item The optional @syntax{ASSIGN} clause specifies how --- at runtime, when @term{file-name-1} is opened --- either a logical device (STDIN, STDOUT) or a file anywhere in one of the currently-mounted file systems will be associated with @term{file-name-1}, as follows:
@enumerate A
@p @item There are three components to the @syntax{ASSIGN} clause --- a @clause{Type} specification (@syntax{EXTERNAL}, @syntax{DYNAMIC} or neither), a @clause{Device} (the list of device choices) and a @clause{Locator} (shown as a choice between @term{identifier-1}, @term{word-1} and @term{literal-1}).
@p @item @syntax{ASSIGN TO DISC '@term{file-name-1}'} will be assumed if there is no @syntax{ASSIGN} clause on a @syntax{SELECT}.
@p @item If an @syntax{ASSIGN} clause is coded without a @clause{Device}, the device @syntax{DISC} will be assumed.
@p @item If a @clause{Locator} clause is coded, the COBOL file @term{file-name-1} will be attached to a data file within any file system that is mounted and available to the executing program at the time @term{file-name-1} is opened.  How that file is identified varies, depending upon the specified @clause{Locator}, as follows:
@enumerate a
@p @item If @term{literal-1} is coded, the value of the literal will serve as the File Location String that will identify the data file.
@p @item If @term{identifier-1} is coded, the value of the identifier will serve as the File Location String that will identify the data file.
@p @item If @term{word-1} (a syntactically valid word not duplicating that of a reserved or user-defined word) is coded, and a @clause{Type} of @syntax{EXTERNAL} is specified, @term{word-1} itself will serve as the File Location String that will identify the data file.  If, however, a @clause{Type} of @syntax{EXTERNAL} was @i{not} specified, the compiler will create a @syntax{PIC X(1024)} data item named @term{word-1} within the program; the contents of that data item at the time the program opens @term{file-name-1} will then serve as the File Location String that will identify the data file.
@p @item File Location Strings will be discussed shortly.
@end enumerate
@item If no @clause{Locator} is coded, @term{file-name-1} will be attached to a logical device or a file based upon the specified (or implied) @clause{Device}, as follows:
@enumerate a
@p @item @syntax{DISC} or @syntax{DISK} will assume an attachment to a file named @term{file-name-1} in whatever directory is current at the time the file is opened.
@p @item @syntax{DISPLAY} will assume an attachment to the @syntax{STDOUT} logical device; these files should only be used for output.
@p @item @syntax{KEYBOARD} will assume an attachment to the @syntax{STDIN} logical device; these files should only be used for input.
@p @item @syntax{PRINTER} will assume an attachment to the @syntax{LPT1} logical device/port; these files should only be used for output.
@p @item @syntax{RANDOM} or @syntax{TAPE} will behave exactly as @syntax{DISC} does.  These two additional @clause{Device}s are provided to facilitate the compilation of COBOL source from other COBOL implementations.
@end enumerate
@item The @syntax{LINE ADVANCING} device @i{requires} that a @clause{Locator} be specified; these files should only be used for output.  A COBOL Line Advancing file will allow carriage-control characters such as line-feeds and form-feeds to be written to the attached operating system file, via the @syntax{ADVANCING} clause of the @statementref{WRITE}.
@p @item File Location Strings are used (at runtime) to identify the path and filename to the data file that must be attached to @term{file-name-1} when that file is opened.
@p @item If the compiler "config" file you used to compile the program with had a "filename-mapping" value of "yes", the GnuCOBOL runtime system will first attempt to identify a currently-defined environment variable whose value will serve as the data file's path and filename, as follows:
@enumerate a
@p @item If the compiler "config" file (@pxref{Compiler Configuration Files}) you used to compile the program specified "mf" as the "assign-clause" value, then the File Locator String will be interpreted according to Microfocus COBOL rules --- namely, everything before the last "-" in the File Locator String will be ignored; the characters after the last "-" will be treated as the base of an environment variable name.  If there is no "-" character in the File Locator String then the entire File Locator String will serve as the base of an environment variable name.  This is the default behaviour for every config file except "ibm".
@p @item If, on the other hand, the compiler "config" file you used to compile the program specified "mf" as the "assign-clause" value, then the File Locator String will be interpreted according to according to IBM COBOL rules --- namely, the File Locator String is expected to be of the form "S-xxx" or "AS-xxx", in which case the "xxx" will be treated as the base of an environment variable name.  If there is no "-" character in the File Locator String then the entire File Locator String will serve as the base of an environment variable name.
@p @item Once an environment variable name base (let's refer to it as "bbbb") has been determined, the runtime system will look for the first one of the following environment variables that exists, in this sequence:
@p @format
DD_bbbb
dd_bbbb
bbbb
@end format
@* Windows systems are case-insensitive with regard to environment variables, so there is no difference between the first two when using a GnuCOBOL implementation built for either Windows/MinGW or native Windows.
@p If an environment variable was found, it's value will serve as the path and filename to the data file.
@end enumerate
@item If no environment variable was found, or the "config" file used to compile the program had a "filename-mapping" value of "no", then the File Locator String value will serve as the path and filename to the data file.
@p @item Paths and file names may be specified on an absolute (@syntax{C:\\Data\\datafile.dat}, @syntax{/Data/datafile.dat}, @dots{}) or relative-to-the-current-directory (@syntax{Data\\datafile.dat}, @syntax{Data/datafile.dat}, @dots{}) basis.
@p There may not even be a path (@syntax{datafile.dat}), in which case the file must be in the current directory.
@end enumerate
@item The @syntaxidx{FILE STATUS} or @syntaxidx{SORT STATUS} clause (they are both equivalent and only one or the other, if any, should be specified) is used to specify the name of a two-digit numeric data item into which an I/O status code will be saved after every I/O verb that is executed against the file.  This does not actually allocate the data item --- you must define the item yourself somewhere in the data division.
@p @anchoridx{File Status Codes}Possible status codes that can be returned to a @syntax{FILE STATUS} data item are as follows:
@p @multitable @columnfractions .06 .94
@headitem Code @tab Explanation
@item 00 @tab Success
@item 02 @tab Success (Duplicate Record Key Written)
@item 05 @tab Success (Optional File Not Found)
@item 07 @tab Success (No Unit)
@item 10 @tab End of file reached if reading forward or beginning-of-file reached if reading backward
@item 14 @tab Out of key range
@item 21 @tab Key invalid
@item 22 @tab Attempt to duplicate key value
@item 23 @tab Key not found
@item 30 @tab Permanent I/O error
@item 31 @tab Inconsistent filename
@item 34 @tab Boundary violation
@item 35 @tab File not found
@item 37 @tab Permission denied
@item 38 @tab Closed with lock
@item 39 @tab Conflicting attribute
@item 41 @tab File already open
@item 42 @tab File not open
@item 43 @tab Read not done
@item 44 @tab Record overflow
@item 46 @tab Read error
@item 47 @tab @syntax{OPEN INPUT} denied (insufficient permissions to read file)
@item 48 @tab @syntax{OPEN OUTPUT} denied (insufficient permissions to write to file)
@item 49 @tab @syntax{OPEN I-O} denied (insufficient permissions to read and/or write file)
@item 51 @tab Record locked
@item 52 @tab End of page
@item 57 @tab @syntax{LINAGE} specifications invalid
@item 61 @tab File sharing failure
@item 91 @tab File not available
@end multitable
@item The @syntaxidx{SHARING} clause defines the conditions under which the program will be willing (or not) to allow other programs executing at the same time to access the file.  @xref{File Sharing}, for the details.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{LOCK} clause defines how concurrent access to the file will be managed on a record-by-record basis.  @xref{Record Locking}, for the details.
@p @item A @syntax{SELECT} statement without an @syntax{ORGANIZATION} explicitly coded will be handled as if the following ORGANIZATION clause had been specified:
@p @example
ORGANIZATION IS SEQUENTIAL
    ACCESS MODE IS SEQUENTIAL
@end example
@end enumerate
