@comment *********************************************************************
@comment ** 5.2.1.1 ORGANIZATION SEQUENTIAL                                 **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newunit{5.2.1.1,ORGANIZATION SEQUENTIAL}
@diagram{ORGANIZATION SEQUENTIAL Clause,ED-SELECT-ORG-SEQ,ED-SELECT-ORG-SEQ,None}@p Files declared as @syntax{ORGANIZATION SEQUENTIAL} will consist of records with no explicit end-of-record delimiter character sequences; records in such files are "delineated" by a calculated byte-offset (based on the maximum record length) into the file.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{BINARY}, @syntax{IS}, @syntax{MODE} and @syntax{RECORD} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{ORGANIZATION} and @syntax{ORGANISATION} are interchangeable.
@p @item The phrase @syntax{ORGANIZATION IS} (and it's internationalized alternative, @syntax{ORGANISATION IS}) is optional to provide compatibility with those (few) COBOL implementations that consider @syntax{ORGANIZATION} to be optional.  Most COBOL implementations do require the word @syntax{ORGANIZATION}, so it should be used in new programs.
@p @item These files cannot be prepared with any standard text-editing or word processing software as all such programs will embed delimiter characters at the end of records (use @syntax{ORGANIZATION IS LINE SEQUENTIAL} instead).
@p @item These files may contain either @syntax{USAGE DISPLAY} or @syntax{USAGE COMPUTATIONAL} (of any variety) data since no binary data sequence can be accidentally interpreted as an end-of-record delimiter.
@p @item While records in a @syntax{ORGANIZATION SEQUENTIAL} file may be defined as having variable-length records, the file will be structured in such a manner as to reserve space for each record equal to the size of the largest possible record, based on the file's description in the @syntax{FILE SECTION}.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{ACCESS MODE SEQUENTIAL} clause is optional because, if absent, it will be assumed anyway for this type of file.  The internal structure of these files is such that they can only be processed in a sequential manner; in order to read the 100th record in such a file, for example, you first must read records 1 through 99.
@p @item Sequential files are processed using the following statements:
@itemize @bullet
@p @item @syntaxref{CLOSE}
@p @item @syntaxref{COMMIT}
@p @item @syntaxref{DELETE}
@p @item @syntaxref{MERGE}
@p @item @syntaxref{OPEN}
@p @item @syntaxref{READ}
@p @item @syntaxref{REWRITE}
@p @item @syntaxref{SORT}
@p @item @syntaxref{UNLOCK}
@p @item @syntaxref{WRITE}
@end itemize
@end enumerate
@comment *********************************************************************
@comment ** 5.2.1.2 ORGANIZATION LINE SEQUENTIAL                            **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newunit{5.2.1.2,ORGANIZATION LINE SEQUENTIAL}
@diagram{ORGANIZATION LINE SEQUENTIAL Clause,ED-SELECT-ORG-L-SEQ,ED-SELECT-ORG-L-SEQ,ED-SELECT-ORG-L-SEQ}@p Files declared as @syntax{ORGANIZATION LINE SEQUENTIAL} will consist of records terminated by an end-of-record delimiter character or character sequence.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{CHARACTER}, @syntax{IS} and @syntax{MODE} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{ORGANIZATION} and @syntax{ORGANISATION} are interchangeable.
@p @item The phrase @syntax{ORGANIZATION IS} (and it's internationalized alternative, @syntax{ORGANISATION IS}) is optional to provide compatibility with those (few) COBOL implementations that consider that word to be optional.  Most COBOL implementations do require the word @syntax{ORGANIZATION}, so it should be used in new programs.
@p @item This is the only @syntax{ORGANIZATION} valid for files that are assigned to the @syntax{PRINTER} device.
@p @item These files may be created with any standard text-editing or word processing software capable of writing text files.  Such files should not contain any @syntax{USAGE COMPUTATIONAL} or @syntax{BINARY} (of any variety) data since such fields could accidentally contain byte sequences that could be interpreted as an end-of-record delimiter.
@p @item Both fixed- and variable-length record formats are supported.
@p @item The end-of-record delimiter sequence will be X'0A' (an ASCII line-feed character) or a X'0D0A' (an ASCII carriage-return + line-feed sequence).  The former is used on Unix implementations of GnuCOBOL (including Windows/MinGW, Windows/Cygwin and OSX implementations) while the latter would be used with native Windows implementations.
@p @item When reading a @syntax{LINE SEQUENTIAL} file, records in excess of the size implied by the file's description in the @syntax{FILE SECTION} will be truncated while records shorter than that size will be padded to the right with @syntax{SPACES}.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{ACCESS MODE SEQUENTIAL} clause is optional because, if absent, it will be assumed anyway for this type of file.  The internal structure of these files is such that the data can only be processed in a sequential manner; in order to read the 100th record in such a file, for example, you first must read records 1 through 99.
@p @item Files assigned to @syntax{PRINTER} or @syntax{CONSOLE} should be specified as @syntax{ORGANIZATION LINE SEQUENTIAL}.
@p @item Line Sequential files are processed using the following statements:
@itemize @bullet
@p @item @syntaxref{CLOSE}
@p @item @syntaxref{COMMIT}
@p @item @syntaxref{DELETE}
@p @item @syntaxref{MERGE}
@p @item @syntaxref{OPEN}
@p @item @syntaxref{READ}
@p @item @syntaxref{REWRITE}
@p @item @syntaxref{SORT}
@p @item @syntaxref{UNLOCK}
@p @item @syntaxref{WRITE}
@end itemize
@end enumerate
@comment *********************************************************************
@comment ** 5.2.1.3 ORGANIZATION RELATIVE                                   **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newunit{5.2.1.3,ORGANIZATION RELATIVE}
@diagram{ORGANIZATION RELATIVE Clause,ED-SELECT-ORG-REL,ED-SELECT-ORG-REL,None}@p These files are files with an internal organization such that records may be processed in a sequential manner based upon their physical location in the file or in a random manner by allowing records to be read, written or updated by specifying the relative record number in the file.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{IS}, @syntax{KEY} and @syntax{MODE} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{ORGANIZATION} and @syntax{ORGANISATION} are interchangeable.
@p @item The phrase @syntax{ORGANIZATION IS} (and it's internationalized alternative, @syntax{ORGANISATION IS}) is optional to provide compatibility with those (few) COBOL implementations that consider that word to be optional.  Most COBOL implementations do require the word @syntax{ORGANIZATION}, so it should be used in new programs.
@p @item @syntax{ORGANIZATION RELATIVE} files cannot be assigned to the @syntax{CONSOLE}, @syntax{DISPLAY}, @syntax{LINE ADVANCING} or @syntax{PRINTER} devices.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{RELATIVE KEY} clause is optional only if @syntax{ACCESS MODE SEQUENTIAL} is specified.
@p @item While an @syntax{ORGANIZATION RELATIVE} file may be defined as having variable-length records, the file will be structured in such a manner as to reserve space for each record equal to the size of the largest possible record as defined by the file's description in the @syntax{FILE SECTION}.
@p @item @syntax{ACCESS MODE SEQUENTIAL}, the default @syntax{ACCESS MODE} if none is specified, indicates that the records of the file will be processed in a sequential manner, according to their physical sequence in the file.
@p @item @syntaxidx{ACCESS MODE RANDOM} means that records will be processed in random sequence by specifying their record number in the file every time the file is read or written.
@p @item @syntaxidx{ACCESS MODE DYNAMIC} indicates the program may switch back and forth between @syntax{SEQUENTIAL} and @syntax{RANDOM} mode during execution.  The file starts out initially in @syntax{SEQUENTIAL} mode when first opened but the program may use the @statementref{START} to switch between sequential and random access.
@p @item The @syntaxidx{RELATIVE KEY} data item is a numeric data item that cannot be defined as a field within records of this file.  Its purpose is to return the current relative record number of a relative file that is being processed in @syntax{SEQUENTIAL} access mode and to serve as a key that specifies the relative record number to be read or written when processing a relative file in @syntax{RANDOM} access mode.
@p @item Relative files are processed using the following statements:
@itemize @bullet
@p @item @syntaxref{CLOSE}
@p @item @syntaxref{COMMIT}
@p @item @syntaxref{DELETE}
@p @item @syntaxref{MERGE}, @syntax{ACCESS MODE RANDOM} not allowed
@p @item @syntaxref{OPEN}
@p @item @syntaxref{READ}
@p @item @syntaxref{REWRITE}
@p @item @syntaxref{SORT}, @syntax{ACCESS MODE RANDOM} not allowed
@p @item @syntaxref{START}
@p @item @syntaxref{UNLOCK}
@p @item @syntaxref{WRITE}
@end itemize
@end enumerate
@comment *********************************************************************
@comment ** 5.2.1.4 ORGANIZATION INDEXED                                    **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newunit{5.2.1.4,ORGANIZATION INDEXED}
@diagram{ORGANIZATION INDEXED Clause,ED-SELECT-ORG-IDX,ED-SELECT-ORG-IDX,None}@p Indexed files, like relative files, may have their records processed in either a sequential or random manner.  Unlike relative files, however, the actual location of a record in an indexed file is calculated automatically based upon the value(s) of one or more alphanumeric fields within records of the file.  For example, an indexed file containing product data might use the product identification code as a record key.  This means you may read, write or update the "A6G4328"th record or the "Z8X7723"th record directly, based upon the product id value of those records!
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{IS}, @syntax{KEY} and @syntax{MODE} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{ORGANIZATION} and @syntax{ORGANISATION} are interchangeable.
@p @item The phrase @syntax{ORGANIZATION IS} (and it's internationalized alternative, @syntax{ORGANISATION IS}) is optional to provide compatibility with those (few) COBOL implementations that consider that word to be optional.  Most COBOL implementations do require the word @syntax{ORGANIZATION}, so it should be used in new programs.
@p @item @syntax{ORGANIZATION INDEXED} files cannot be assigned to @syntax{CONSOLE}, @syntax{DISPLAY}, @syntax{KEYBOARD}, @syntax{LINE ADVANCING} or @syntax{PRINTER}.
@p @item @syntaxidx{ACCESS MODE SEQUENTIAL}, the default @syntax{ACCESS MODE} if none is specified,  indicates that the records of the file will be processed in a sequential manner with respect to the values of the @syntax{RECORD KEY} or the @syntax{ALTERNATE RECORD KEY} most-recently referenced on a @statementref{START}.
@p @item @syntaxidx{ACCESS MODE RANDOM} means that records will be processed in random sequence by accessing the record with specific record key or alternate record key values.
@p @item @syntaxidx{ACCESS MODE DYNAMIC} allows the file will be processed either in @syntax{RANDOM} or @syntax{SEQUENTIAL} mode; the program may switch between the two modes as needed.  The @syntax{START} statement is used to make the switch between modes.
@p @item  The @syntaxidx{RECORD KEY} clause defines the field within the record used to provide the primary access to records within the file.  No two records in the file will be allowed to have the same @syntax{PRIMARY KEY} field value. The @syntaxidx{SOURCE IS} clause is for use with split keys.
@p @item  The @syntaxidx{ALTERNATE RECORD KEY} clause, if used, defines an additional field within the record that provides an alternate means of directly accessing records or an additional field by which the file's contents may be processed sequentially.  You have the choice of allowing records to have duplicate alternate key values, if necessary.
@p @item There may be multiple @syntax{ALTERNATE RECORD KEY} clauses, each defining an additional alternate key for the file.
@p @item Usage of the @syntaxidx{SUPPRESS WHEN} clause is used when @syntaxidx{Sparse Keys} are required which may take the form for a literal or spaces or zeroes.
@p @item Indexed files are processed using the following statements:
@itemize @bullet
@p @item @syntaxref{CLOSE}
@p @item @syntaxref{COMMIT}
@p @item @syntaxref{DELETE}
@p @item @syntaxref{MERGE}, @syntax{ACCESS MODE RANDOM} not allowed
@p @item @syntaxref{OPEN}
@p @item @syntaxref{READ}
@p @item @syntaxref{REWRITE}
@p @item @syntaxref{SORT}, @syntax{ACCESS MODE RANDOM} not allowed
@p @item @syntaxref{START}
@p @item @syntaxref{UNLOCK}
@p @item @syntaxref{WRITE}
@end itemize
@end enumerate
@comment *********************************************************************
@comment ** 5.2.2 SAME RECORD AREA Statement                                **
@comment *********************************************************************
@page
@newsubsection{5.2.2,SAME RECORD AREA}
@diagram{I-O-CONTROL SAME AREA,ED-IO-CONTROL-SAME,ED-IO-CONTROL-SAME,ED-IO-CONTROL-SAME}@p The @syntax{SAME RECORD AREA} clause allows you to specify that multiple files should share the same input and output memory buffers.
@enumerate
@p @item The reserved words @syntax{AREA} and @syntax{FOR} are optional and may be included, or not, at the discretion of the programmer.  The presence or absence of these words has no effect upon the program.
@p @item This statement must be terminated with a period.
@p @item While coding only a single file name (the repeated @term{file-name-1} item) is syntactically valid, this statement will have no effect upon the program unless at least two files are specified.
@p @item The effect of this statement will be to cause the specified files to share the same I/O buffer in memory.  These buffers can sometimes get quite large, and by having multiple files share the same buffer memory you may significantly cut down the amount of memory the program is using (thus making "room" for more procedural code or data).  If you do use this feature, take care to ensure that no more than one of the specified files are ever OPEN simultaneously.
@end enumerate
